      "side": 1,
      "message": "In your first example, it has two returns total (count_all_returns\u003d2) and one return as the last statement in the top level block (count_returns_at_end_of_control_flow\u003d1). count_returns_at_end_of_control_flow will not see the if statement because it\u0027s not the last statement of the top-level block; it only recurses into the `return` statement at the end. So early-return detection should work fine here.\n\nYour second example isn\u0027t eligible for inlining at all because it has a return inside of a loop or switch, i.e. count_returns_in_breakable_constructs !\u003d 0. However, ignoring that... count_all_returns\u003d1 (correct) and count_returns_at_end_of_control_flow\u003d1 (oops). You\u0027re right, that\u0027s incorrect. It should be count_returns_at_end_of_control_flow\u003d0. I\u0027ll fix that. I thought of that case and added in the \"!inLoopOrSwitch\" check to the if statement, but on deeper inspection, that wasn\u0027t good enough. I\u0027ll try again.",
